Tidy data frames

The tidyverse is a collection of R packages that help solve data science challenges. This collection of packages share the same design philosophy, grammar, and data structures. You can install the collection of tidyverse packages in R by running install.packages("tidyverse") in the console. To attach the packges within an R session, run the following:

library(tidyverse)

Within the tidyverse paradigm, the main data structure of interest is the tibble. A tibble is a data frame with specific default behavior.

Broadly, tibbles consist of rows and columns, where the length of the rows is consistent for all columns. For example, here is a tibble with two columns, x and y, each with three rows.

tibble(
  x = c(1, 2, 3),
  y = c(4, 5, 6)
)

Exercise

Create a tibble using the tibble() function consisting of two variables, x and y, detailed below.

x <- c(1, 2, 3)
y <- c("do", "re", "mi")
x <- c(1, 2, 3)
y <- c("do", "re", "mi")
tibble(x = x, y = y)

Variable classes

Each column in a tibble has a specific class.

Common column classes include:

class definition example
double (numeric) double-precision floating point number 1.5
integer (numeric) whole number 1L
logical logical constant, either TRUE or FALSE TRUE
character a character string "this is a string"
list an ordered collection of components that can be of different modes and types list(1, "two", 3)

Every element in the column must belong to the same class. For example, here is a tibble with

tibble(
  numeric = 1:5,
  logical = TRUE,
  character = LETTERS[1:5]
)

Notice here the class of the column is printed below the variable name. The first column numeric is an integer, as indicated by int. The second column logical is logical, as indicated by lgl. The third column character is a character string, as indicated by chr. Also notice that even though TRUE was only entered once, it is repeated 5 times to match the length of the other columns. Tibbles will automatically recycle inputs of length 1.

tibble(
  a = c(1, 2, 3),
  b = c("one", "two", "three"),
  c = list("one", 2, "three")
)

Saving tibbles

You can save a tibble locally during an R session by assigning it to a name using <-. For example, the code below assigns the tibble to df.

df <- tibble(
  numeric = 1:5,
  logical = TRUE,
  character = LETTERS[1:5]
)

Exercise

Create a tibble from the two vectors below, x and y. Assign this tibble to dat.

x <- c(8, 6, 7)
y <- c(5, 3, 0)
dat <- tibble(
  x = c(8, 6, 7),
  y = c(5, 3, 0)
)

Subsetting tibbles

You can subset a tibble by using a single square bracket [row(s), column(s)], indicating the rows and columns you’d like to keep by number, or using the double square bracket, [[column]] to extract a single column, indicated by name or by position. For example below, if I wanted to subset df to only contain rows 1 and 2 and column 3, I would use the single square bracket as follows.

tibble(
  numeric = 1:5,
  logical = TRUE,
  character = LETTERS[1:5]
)
df[c(1, 2), 3]

Alternatively, I could use the double square brackets to extract the character column and output just the values. The code below does this by name.

df[["character"]]
## [1] "A" "B" "C" "D" "E"

Equivalently, I can do this by position, since character is the third column in the df tibble.

df[[3]]
## [1] "A" "B" "C" "D" "E"

Reading tidy data

You can read data into R using read_*() functions. These include:

  • read_csv(): Reads in .csv files by default
  • read_delim(): Reads in tab-delimited files by default

The first argument of each of these functions is the file, the name of the file where the data are to be read from.

For example, we have a file sleep.csv in a folder called data that contains data on the effect of two drugs on 10 patients’ sleep.

"extra","group","ID"
 0.7,   "1",    "1"
-1.6,   "1",    "2"
-0.2,   "1",    "3"
-1.2,   "1",    "4"
-0.1,   "1",    "5"
.        .       . 
.        .       . 
.        .       . 
read_csv(file = "data/sleep.csv")
## 
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## cols(
##   extra = col_double(),
##   group = col_double(),
##   ID = col_double()
## )

We can save this data frame to an object in R using the assignment operator, <-

sleep_data <- read_csv(file = "data/sleep.csv")
## 
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## cols(
##   extra = col_double(),
##   group = col_double(),
##   ID = col_double()
## )

Manipulating tidy data

In this section, we’re focusing on how to use a core tidyverse package to manipulate data: the dplyr package.

To explore dplyr’s basic data manipulation methods, we will learn how to use the following functions:

  • Subset or filter() a data frame’s observations by picking their values
  • Pick variables or select() a data frame’s columns
  • Add or mutate() variables to a data frame
  • Condense or summarize() variables down to a single summary

Filtering or subsetting rows

To filter rows of a data frame, you can use the filter() function. As an example, we will manipulate the flight data frame from the nycflights13 package.

This data frame includes 336,776 flights that departed from New York City in 2013. The data comes from the US Bureau of Transportation Statistics.

flights

If you wanted to filter this data frame to only include rows of flights that only went out on January 1st, you would do the following:

filter(flights, month == 1, day == 1)

Notice the first argument is the original data frame, flights, and the subsequent arguments are the logical predicates defined in terms of the variables in the original data frame. The first argument for all functions used to manipulate data in the tidyverse is the data frame you are manipulating. When you run the above line of code, dplyr executes the filtering operation and returns a new data frame.

filter(flights, month == 1, day == 1)

dplyr functions never alter their inputs. If you want to save the results, you must use the assignment operator <-

jan1 <- filter(flights, month == 1, day == 1)

If you want to filter the data frame based on more than one condition, you can use logical operators.

For example, if you want to only include rows of flights that weren’t delayed (on arrival or departure) by more than two hours, you would do the following:

filter(flights, arr_delay <= 120, dep_delay <= 120)

Exercise

Modify the code below to filter the flights data frame to only include rows of flights that went out on December 25th:

filter(flights, month == 1, day == 1)
filter(flights, month == 12, day == 25)

Selecting or subsetting columns

To select specific columns, you can use the select() function. For example, if you want to create a data frame that only includes the year column, you can do the following:

select(flights, year)

Notice again that the first argument of the select() function is the data frame that is being manipulated, in this case flights. The subsequent arguments are the variables that you would like to select. If you would like to only include year, month, and day you can do the following:

select(flights, year, month, day)

Alternatively, you can use expressions like x:y to select ranges of variables. For example, since the columns year, month, day in the flights data frame are in that order, we can select them as follows:

select(flights, year:day)

If you would like to include all columns except year, month, and day you can use the - sign as shown below:

select(flights, -(year:day))

Exercises

Create a new data frame called flights_month that only includes the month column from the flights data frame.

select(flights, month)

Filter the flights data frame to only include rows where arr_delay is less than or equal to 120 minutes and select the following columns: dep_time, sched_dep_time.

select(filter(flights, arr_delay <= 120),
       dep_time, sched_dep_time)

Add variables to a data frame

We can add new columns that are transformations of existing columns with the mutate() function. The mutate() function always adds new columns to the end of the data set.

For example, we can add two columns to the flights data frame using the mutate() function as follows:

mutate(flights,
       gain = dep_delay - arr_delay,
       speed = distance / air_time * 60
)

Notice again that the first argument is the data frame being manipulated and the subsequent arguments are name-value pairs of expressions with the name indicating the name of the new variable being created and the value it’s corresponding value.

If you only want to keep the new variables, use transmute():

transmute(flights,
          gain = dep_delay - arr_delay,
          hours = air_time / 60,
          gain_per_hour = gain / hours
)

Exercise

Using the flights data, add a variable speed that is equal to distance / air_time * 60:

mutate(flights,
       speed = distance / air_time * 60
)

Summarize columns in a data frame

With dplyr, you can use functions to summarize observations in a column of a data frame using the summarize() function and the group_by() function.

For example, we can calculate the average delay per date by running the following:

by_day <- group_by(flights, year, month, day)
summarize(by_day, delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year', 'month'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Notice that the first argument of both group_by() and summarize() is the data frame being grouped and summarized, respectively. Note, when using aggregation functions, we have an na.rm = TRUE argument that removes missing values before computation.

Exercise

Calculate the average amount of time spent in the air, air_time by year in the flights data frame. Group the flight data by year and then summarize the mean air_time.

by_year <- group_by(---, ---)
summarize(by_year, mean(----, na.rm = TRUE))
by_year <- group_by(flights, year)
summarize(by_year, mean(air_time, na.rm = TRUE))

Pipes

Rather than giving each data frame a name, we can use the pipe: %>%.

  • The pipe improves the readability of code since you can read the code from left-to-right
  • We can read it as a series of commands for example: group, then summarize, then filter

For example here’s a summary of the flights average departure delay, dep_delay, grouped by year, month, and day:

flights %>% 
  group_by(year, month, day) %>% 
  summarize(mean = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year', 'month'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Suppose we want to remove the missing values prior to our calculation. We can solve this issue by removing all flights missing departure times from the data set then grouping, then summarising.

flights %>% 
  filter(!is.na(dep_delay)) %>%
  group_by(year, month, day) %>% 
  summarize(mean = mean(dep_delay))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year', 'month'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Exercise

Using the flights data, find the the flights average distance grouped by year, origin, dest, and arr_delay. Call this new column mean_distance.

flights %>% 
  group_by(year, origin, dest, arr_delay) %>% 
  summarize(mean_distance = mean(distance, na.rm = TRUE))

Vectors, Lists, and Data frames

Numeric vectors

R operates on data structures. The simplest data structure is a numeric vector, defined as an ordered collection of numbers. A single number is a vector of length 1, for example, in the code below, a vector with a single number, 3, is assigned to x.

x <- 3

A vector with multiple numeric components can be created using the c() function, which concatenates each element. For example, a vector consisting of three numbers, 9, 2, and 8 can be assigned to x with the following code.

x <- c(9, 2, 8)

Exercise

Create a vector with 4 elements: 2, 4, 6, 8

c(2, 4, 6, 8)

Vector arithmetic

Arithmetic can be performed on vectors; the expressions will be applied element by element. For example, two vectors can be added using the +, as seen below.

c(1, 2, 3) + c(3, 2, 1)
## [1] 4 4 4

If the vectors are not of the same length, the elements of the shorter vector(s) will be recycled to complete the expression.

c(1, 2) + c(1, 2, 3, 4)
## [1] 2 4 4 6

For example, above the vector c(1, 2) was repeated so that it has length 4, resulting in c(1, 2, 1, 2) to match the length of c(1, 2, 3, 4).

Additional common arithmetic functions include:

  • log()
  • exp()
  • sqrt()
  • min()
  • max()
  • mean()
  • var()

Exercises

Edit the code below to multiply vector x by vector y.

x <- c(1, 8, 6, 7)
y <- c(5, 3, 0, 9)
x <- c(1, 8, 6, 7)
y <- c(5, 3, 0, 9)
x * y

Take the log() of the vector x below and multiply this result by 10.

x <- c(1, 8, 6, 7)
x <- c(1, 8, 6, 7)
log(x) * 10

Logical vectors

In addition to numeric vectors, R also allows for logical vectors. These vectors can consist of the values: TRUE, FALSE, and NA (meaning “not available” indicating a missing value). These vectors are generated by conditions, created with the following logicial operators:

  • <: less than
  • <=: less than or equal to
  • >: greater than
  • >=: greater than or equal to
  • ==: equal
  • !=: not equal
  • &: logical AND (element wise comparison)
  • &&: logical AND (evaluates left to right, examining only the first element of each vector)
  • |: logical OR (element wise comparison)
  • ||: logical OR (evalutes left to right, examining only the first element of each vector)
  • !: logical negtation (NOT)

For example, the following code creates a logical vector assessing whether each element of the vector x is greater than 4

x <- c(8, 6, 7, 5, 3, 0, 9)
x > 4
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE  TRUE

Exercises

Check whether each element of x is greater than or equal to 3.

x <- c(8, 6, 7, 5, 3, 0, 9)
x <- c(8, 6, 7, 5, 3, 0, 9)
x >= 3

Check whether each element of x is greater than 5 AND less than or equal to 7.

x <- c(8, 6, 7, 5, 3, 0, 9)
x <- c(8, 6, 7, 5, 3, 0, 9)
x > 5 & x <= 7

Character vectors

It is also possible to store character values in a vector. Character strings are entered in R using quotation marks, either ' or ", for example below is a character vector with the first three letters in the alphabet.

c("a", "b", "c")
## [1] "a" "b" "c"

Exercise

Create a character vector with the values: “apple” “banana” and “pear”

c("apple", "banana", "pear")

Indexing vectors

You can index a vector by using a square bracket, [] with the desired index vector. There are four types of index vectors

  1. A logical vector
  2. A vector of positive integers
  3. A vector of negative integers
  4. A character vector

Logicial vectors

Using a logical vector, x, to index another vector, y, will select only the values of y for which the conditions for x are TRUE. For example, if x is c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE), the first and third element of y will be selected. It works like this. The x vector, or the logical index vector, will be placed in a square bracket appended to the vector y.

y <- c(1, 2, 3)
y[c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE)]
## [1] 1 3

Vectors of positive integers

Using a vector of positive integers, x, to index another vector, y, will select only the values of y that correspond to the position dictated by x. For example, if x is c(1, 2), the first and second element of y will be selected.

y <- c(3, 4, 5)
y[c(1, 2)]
## [1] 3 4

Vectors of negative integers

Using a vector of negative integers, x, to index another vector, y, will select only the values of y that correspond to the position NOT in x. For example, if x is -c(1, 2), the first and second element of y will NOT be selected.

y <- c(3, 4, 5)
y[-c(1, 2)]
## [1] 5

Vectors of character strings

If a vector has a names attribute, the elements can be selected using a character vector.

fruits <- c(1, 2, 3)
names(fruits) <- c("apple", "banana", "pear")
fruits[c("pear", "apple")]
##  pear apple 
##     3     1

Exercise

Select the second, fourth, and fifth elements of the vector, x, below.

x <- 1:10

Lists

An R list is data structure consisting of an ordered collection of components. The components can be of different modes and types, for example, a list could be a collection of different types of vectors of different lengths, as seen below.

list(numeric = c(1, 2, 3), 
     logical = TRUE,
     character = c("apple", "banana"))
## $numeric
## [1] 1 2 3
## 
## $logical
## [1] TRUE
## 
## $character
## [1] "apple"  "banana"

Components of the list are numbered and can be referenced using a double bracket. For example, you can reference the first element of a list with [[1]] as seen below.

lst <- list(numeric = c(1, 2, 3), 
     logical = TRUE,
     character = c("apple", "banana"))
lst[[1]]
## [1] 1 2 3

Components can also be referenced via their names. For example, the first element of the list below could be referenced by [["numeric"]]

lst[["numeric"]]
## [1] 1 2 3

Data frames

A data frame is a specific type of list with the class data.frame or tibble. A tibble is a specific subclass of data.frame that has a few additional restrictions. Broadly, data frames consist of rows and columns, where the length of the rows is consistent for all columns. For example, here is a data frame with two columns, x and y, each with three rows.

data.frame(
  x = c(1, 2, 3),
  y = c(4, 5, 6)
)

  • read.csv(): Reads in .csv files by default
  • read.delim(): Reads in tab-delimited files by default

The first argument of each of these functions is the file, the name of the file where the data are to be read from.

For example, we have a file sleep.csv in a folder called data that contains data on the effect of two drugs on 10 patients’ sleep.

Manipulating data

You can manipulate data frames. In this lesson, we will learn how to:

  • Filter or subset a data frame’s rows based on particular conditions
  • Select or subset a data frame’s columns
  • Add variables to a data frame
  • Summarize columns in a data frame

Filtering or subsetting rows

To filter rows of a data frame, you can use the subset() function with the subset argument. For example, here is a data frame included in R called mtcars. This data was extracted from the 1974 Motor Trend US magazine, and comprises fuel consumption and 10 aspects of automobile design and performance for 32 automobiles (1973–74 models).

mtcars

If you wanted to filter this data frame to only include rows of cars that have miles per gallon (mpg) greater than 25, you would do the following:

subset(mtcars, subset = mpg > 25)

You can save this new filtered data frame by assigning it to a new object using the <-:

mtcars_subset <- subset(mtcars, subset = mpg > 25)

If you want to subset based on more than one condition, you can use logical operators discussed in a previous section. For example, if you want to filter to only include rows where mpg is greater than 25 and weight (wt) is greater than 2, you would do the following:

subset(mtcars, subset = mpg > 25 & wt > 2)

Exercise

Filter the mtcars data frame to only include rows where the gross horsepower (hp) is less than 100.

mtcars
subset(mtcars, hp < 100)

Selecting or subsetting columns

To select specific columns, you can also use the subset() function. Instead of specifying the subset argument (that would filter the rows), you can specify the select argument to select specific columns. For example, if you want to create a data frame that only includes the mpg column, you can do the following:

subset(mtcars, select = mpg)

If you would like to only include both mpg and cyl, you can pass a vector, c(mpg, cyl) to the select argument.

subset(mtcars, select = c(mpg, cyl))

If you would like to include all columns except mpg, you can use the - sign as shown below.

subset(mtcars, select = - mpg)

Exercises

Create a new data frame called mtcars_disp that only includes the disp column from the mtcars data frame.

mtcars_disp <- subset(mtcars, select = disp)

Create a new data frame called mtcars_new that filters rows to only include rows where wt is less than 2 and selects two columns, wt and mpg.

mtcars_new <- subset(mtcars, subset = wt < 2, select = c(wt, mpg))

Add variables to a data frame

There are many ways to add a column to a data frame. Two are the following:

  • via the $
  • via the cbind() function

A variable can be referenced in a data frame using the $. For example, using the mtcars data frame, you can reference the mpg column using mtcars$mpg. You can add a new variable by assigning a vector to the new variable, as below:

mtcars$new_var <- 1:32

Alternatively, a new variable can be added using the cbind() function. In order to ensure that this new variable is saved, you must assign the new data frame created with cbind()

new_var <- 1:32

mtcars <- cbind(mtcars, new_var)

Exercise

Below is a data frame called df with one variable, x. Add a variable called y that is equal to c(1, 2, 3). Then output df.

df <- data.frame(x = c("a", "b", "c"))
## Add a variable called y
df
df <- data.frame(x = c("a", "b", "c"))
df$y <- c(1, 2, 3)
df

Summarise columns in a data frame

In R, you can use functions to summarise observations in a column of a data frame. For example, to take the average, or mean, of a column, you can use the mean() function and reference the data frame’s column using the $. To take the average of the miles per gallon (mpg) column in the mtcars data frame, you would run the following:

mean(mtcars$mpg)
## [1] 20.09062

If you want to summarise observations in a column by another column, one way to do this is using the aggregate() function. For example, if you wanted to calculate the average miles per gallon (mpg) by the number of cylinders (cyl) using the mtcars data, you would run the following:

aggregate(mpg ~ cyl, data = mtcars, FUN = mean)

If instead of taking the average, you wanted to take sum the miles per gallon (mpg) by the number of cylinders (cyl), you would change the FUN argument to sum as below:

aggregate(mpg ~ cyl, data = mtcars, FUN = sum)

Exercise

Using the mtcars data, calculate the average weight (wt) by the transmission (am).
